===Etymology 3===
From [[Dharuk]] language ''[[diyin]]'' or ''[[dyin]]'', but acquiring a derogatory tone.  (Reference: [[w:R. M. W. Dixon|R. M. W. Dixon]], Australian Aboriginal Words'', Oxford University Press, 1990, ISBN 0-19-553099-3, page 167.)

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# (''Australian'') an [[Aboriginal|Aboriginal]] [[woman]] - ''(now considered [[offensive]])''
#:*'''1988''': Dad said Shoesmith and Thompson had made one error that cost them their lives by letting the '''gins''' into the camp, and the blacks speared them all. — Tom Cole, ''Hell West and Crooked'' (Angus&Robertson 1995 p.179)

